  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Performing background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Reporting suspicious activities to authorities\n- Filing currency transaction reports\n- Documenting large cash transactions\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees on AML regulations\n- Implementing screening processes\n- Conducting risk assessments\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Identifying and verifying customer information\n- Understanding customer business activities\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n\n5. Legal Consequences\n- Potential significant financial penalties\n- Risk of criminal prosecution\n- Loss of operating licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced through laws like the Bank Secrecy Act and regulated by agencies such as FinCEN in the United States.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific aspects of money laundering regulations?",
